{ SolarSystem

  table { ll
  `setFlagLabels` ☰ toggles if Planets' and their Moons' names are shown next to them. This functionality seems to correspond to the `alt-p` → Wissenschaft/Astronomie/tools/Stellarium#stellarium-shortcut[keyboard shortcut].
  → Wissenschaft/Astronomie/tools/Stellarium/script/API/SolarSystem/setFlagPlanets[`setFlagPlanets`] ☰
  → Wissenschaft/Astronomie/tools/Stellarium/script/API/SolarSystem/setFlagTrails[`setFlagTrails`] ☰
  `setMaxTrailPoints` ☰ sets the maximum number of trail lines that each object draws behind itself if → Wissenschaft/Astronomie/tools/Stellarium/script/API/SolarSystem/setFlagTrails[`setFlagTrails(true)`] was called.
  table }

}
{ StelMovementMgr

  table { ll
   `setAutoMoveDuration` ☰ Sets the duration for an auto-move operation (such as → Wissenschaft/Astronomie/tools/Stellarium/script/API/core/selectObjectByName[`core.selectObjectByName()`] followed by → Wissenschaft/Astronomie/tools/Stellarium/script/API/StelMovementMgr/setFlagTracking[`StelMovementMgr.setFlagTracking()`]?)
    → Wissenschaft/Astronomie/tools/Stellarium/script/API/StelMovementMgr/setFlagTracking[`setFlagTracking`] ☰
    → Wissenschaft/Astronomie/tools/Stellarium/script/API/StelMovementMgr/setMaxFov[`setMaxFov`] ☰ *Fov* stands for *field of view*.
    → Wissenschaft/Astronomie/tools/Stellarium/script/API/StelMovementMgr/zoomTo[`zoomTo`] ☰ Change the *field of view*.
  table }
}
{ Parameters that expect an angle #stellarium-parameters-angle

  Some functions that are exposed through Stellarium's API, such as → Wissenschaft/Astronomie/tools/Stellarium/script/API/core/moveToAltAzi[`core.moveToAltAzi`] or
  → Wissenschaft/Astronomie/tools/Stellarium/script/API/core/moveToRaDec[`core.moveToRaDec`] have parameters that expect a value that represents an angle.

  There are → https://stellarium.org/doc/0.15/namespaceStelUtils.html#acd88f8194549c7d46656952428720427[multiple formats] with which these angles can be specified:
    • `+53d 51'21.6" - +53d51'21.6"`
    • `-1d 10'31.8" - +46d6'31"`
    • `50D46'0"N - 123D47'59"W`
    • `123.567 N`
    • `123.567W`
    • `-123.567`
    • `12h 14m 6s`

? The `D` or `d` in the examples above is the *degree separator. Instead of the degree separator, the real degree symbol (`º`, 0xBA, not to be confused with `°`, 0xB0) can be used instead.

  See also → https://stellarium.org/doc/0.20/namespaceStelUtils.html#acd88f8194549c7d46656952428720427[`double StelUtils::getDecAngle(const QString & str)`] which
  converts the angle to radians.

}
